        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">How many exercises should a workout have?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">A typical workout should include 4-8 exercises depending on duration and intensity. A 15-minute session might have 4 exercises, while a 60-minute session can include 7-8 exercises. Quality of movement and proper form matter more than the number of exercises. This generator automatically adjusts exercise count based on your selected duration.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">How long should I rest between sets?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">Rest periods depend on your training goal. For strength (heavy weight, low reps), rest 2-3 minutes. For hypertrophy (moderate weight, 8-12 reps), rest 60-90 seconds. For endurance or fat loss (lighter weight, high reps), rest 30-60 seconds. This generator assigns appropriate rest times based on exercise type and difficulty level.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">Can I build muscle with bodyweight exercises only?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">Yes, bodyweight exercises can build significant muscle, especially for beginners and intermediates. Push-ups, pull-ups, dips, squats, and lunges are proven muscle builders. Progress by increasing reps, slowing the tempo, adding pauses, or moving to harder variations. This generator includes a full library of bodyweight exercises across all muscle groups.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">How often should I train each muscle group?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">Most research suggests training each muscle group 2-3 times per week for optimal growth. Allow at least 48 hours of recovery between sessions targeting the same muscles. Full body workouts 3 times per week or an upper/lower split 4 times per week are both effective approaches for most people.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="faq-item">
          <div class="faq-question">What is the difference between beginner and advanced workouts?</div>
          <div class="faq-answer">Beginner workouts use simpler movements, fewer sets, higher reps with lighter loads, and longer rest periods. Advanced workouts incorporate compound supersets, higher volume, shorter rest periods, and more challenging exercise variations like plyometrics and unilateral movements. Intermediate sits between, introducing moderate complexity and volume.</div>
